'''Hamdi Aslan''' (born September 6, 1967) is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[association football|football]] [[Coach (sports)|coach]] and former footballer. Between 2006 and 2010, he served as the head coach of the [[Turkey women's national football team]].<ref name="tff0"/><ref name="tff1"/><ref name="tff2"/>

==Playing career==
===Club===
Aslan began his playing career at his local club [[Trabzonspor]]'s youth team. Between 1990 and 1996, he played in the senior team, the first season in the |[[TFF First League]], and then in the [[Süper Lig]].<ref name="r2"/><ref name="s1"/> During this time, he capped 156 times and scored 16 goals in the league matches, and enjoyed three [[Turkish Cup]], two [[Turkish Super Cup|President's Cup]] and three Prime Minister's Cup titles with his club.<ref name="s1"/> In the 1996–97 season, Aslan transferred to the [[TFF Second League]] club [[Adanaspor]], where he appeared in 88 matches and netted 23 goals in total.<ref name="tff0"/>

Hamdi Aslan is remembered for his fair play and his head goals for Trabzonspor.<ref name="sp"/>

===International===
He was admitted to the [[Turkey national youth football team|Turkey U-18]] team, and debuted in the [[1986 UEFA European Under-18 Championship qualifying#Group 8|1986 UEFA European Under-18 Championship qualifying – Group 8]] match against the Czech team on April 18, 1985.<ref name="tff3"/> Aslan took part in three of the six matches at the tournament. He capped 9 times for the Turkey youth team.<ref name="tff0"/>

His first appearance in the [[Turkey national under-21 football team|Turkey U-21]] was in the friendly match against [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romanian juniors]] on March 3, 1987.<ref name="tff4"/> He played in one of the four matches at the [[1988 UEFA European Under-21 Championship#Qualifying Stage|1988 UEFA European Under-21 Championship – Qualifying Stage Group 4]], and in five of the six matches at the [[1990 UEFA European Under-21 Championship#Qualifying Stage|1990 UEFA European Under-21 Championship – Qualifying Stage Group 3]]. Aslan capped nine times for the Turkey U-21 team.<ref name="tff0"/>

He was seven times part of the [[Turkey national football team]], six of them at the 1987 Mediterranean Cup.<ref name="tff0"/>

==Managing career==
Hamdi Aslan managed the team [[Akçaabat Sebatspor]] in his hometown in the 2005–06 season, before he was appointed head coach of the [[Turkey women's national football team|Turkey women's national team]] in 2006. Coaching also the women's junior and girls' youth teams, he served at this position until 2010.<ref name="tff2"/><ref name="r1"/><ref name="s1"/><ref name="h1"/><ref name="s2"/>

